President Obama announced his intent to nominate Anne C. Richard as Assistant Secretary for Population, Refugees and Migration at the Department of State. Richard is currently the Vice President of Government Relations and Advocacy for the International Rescue Committee (IRC). She has previously held positions at the Department of State and the Peace Corps. Richard has a B.S. in Foreign Service from Georgetown University and an M.A. in Public Policy Studies from the University of Chicago.

Tara D. Sonenshine was nominated as Under Secretary for Public Diplomacy and Public Affairs at the Department of State. Sonenshine is currently the Executive Vice President of the United States Institute of Peace (USIP). She has also worked as a strategic communications adviser to various international organizations and served in the White House during the Clinton Administration. Sonenshine holds a B.A. in Political Science from Tufts University.

President Obama also announced his intent to appoint Lauren Elizabeth Potter and Julie Ann Petty as members of the President's Committee for People with Intellectual Disabilities. Potter is a cast member on the television show Glee and is involved in disability rights advocacy. Petty is a project trainer for Partners for Inclusive Communities at the Arkansas University Center on Disabilities and has worked with various disability organizations.